http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 9 Mar 2015
Source: OIE, WAHID weekly disease information 2015; 28(11) [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=17327


Foot-and-mouth disease, Botswana
--------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 9 Mar 2015 from Dr Letlhogile Modisa, Director, Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture, Gaborone, Botswana

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 9 Mar 2015
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 9 Mar 2015
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 20 May 2014
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: Foot and mouth disease virus
Serotype: pending
Nature of diagnosis: clinical
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Maxebo crush, Kareng, Zone 2d, Nganiland, [North West District]
Date of start of the outbreak: 9 Mar 2015
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: village
Total animals affected
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 500 / 20 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: Cattle grazing in communal area in a subzone that is routinely vaccinated for FMD.

Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Cattle / 4 / 0 / 0 / 0
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive; contact with wild species.

Epidemiological comments: The suspected outbreak is located outside the FMD free zones without vaccination. An animal with oral lesions was detected during clinical inspection prior to loading for slaughter at the local abattoir. Trace-back to the origin revealed a further 19 cases with clinical signs similar to those of FMD. No other cases have been reported in the rest of zone 2d. Samples have been collected and submitted to the laboratory, and results are awaited. Epidemiological investigations are still continuing. Weekly reports will be submitted.

Control measures
Measures applied: control of wildlife reservoirs, zoning, no vaccination, no treatment of affected animals.
Measures to be applied: movement control inside the country, vaccination in response to the outbreak(s) and dipping/spraying

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Botswana Vaccine Institute (OIE's reference laboratory) / Cattle / virus isolation / Pending

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[On 27 Oct 2014, Botswana reported foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) in the Ngamiland region [North West District], located in Zone 2c. Serotype SAT1 was identified. Two outbreaks were reported in cattle, and 24 116 cattle have been vaccinated in response to these outbreaks. The vaccine applied was a Trivalent SAT 1, 2 and 3 vaccine.

The last follow-up report submitted by Bostwana for this October 2014 event was on 20 Feb 2015. The follow-up report No. 3 indicates that the event continues and that future follow-up reports will be sent. The report and map are available at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_fup_0000017228_20150220_182318.pdf.

This last event (March 2015) was reported to occur in Zone 2d and is likely to be related to the occurrences in the rest of Zone 2 in 2014.

For background information on FMD in Botswana, see comments in ProMED-mail archive numbers 20140627.2568443 and 20141029.2913660.

A map of Botswana can be seen at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Districts_of_Botswana. - Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3219940,16992.]
